30% to 40% is actually

00:52:54.600 --> 00:52:57.660
one that's good to keep in
mind because other studies that

00:52:57.660 --> 00:53:01.380
have looked at the rise
of authoritarianism

00:53:01.380 --> 00:53:03.720
in Europe and the
propensity to support

00:53:03.720 --> 00:53:06.570
authoritarian
leadership seems to find

00:53:06.570 --> 00:53:11.050
a steady rate of around 35%,
particularly of young people.

00:53:11.050 --> 00:53:12.960
And this is something
to be aware of-- what

00:53:12.960 --> 00:53:17.290
we call the millennial or
the zoomers generation who,

00:53:17.290 --> 00:53:19.530
you know, would respond
to questions that

00:53:19.530 --> 00:53:21.900
would support authoritarianism.

00:53:21.900 --> 00:53:24.120
And this is also
happening in a context

00:53:24.120 --> 00:53:29.070
where we have the rise
of national populism,

00:53:29.070 --> 00:53:32.970
ethno-nationalism, and a lot
of cross traffic of these ideas

00:53:32.970 --> 00:53:34.980
that are moving from the
alternative-- you know,

00:53:34.980 --> 00:53:39.600
alternative for Germany,
to what's happened recently

00:53:39.600 --> 00:53:42.060
with the elections
in the Netherlands,

00:53:42.060 --> 00:53:43.500
to what happened in New Zealand.

00:53:43.500 --> 00:53:46.380
So it's really important to put
it in a transnational context.

00:53:48.930 --> 00:53:50.670
My idea is to not--

00:53:50.670 --> 00:53:52.620
I don't want to
sensationalize this.

00:53:52.620 --> 00:53:54.300
But we also don't
want to trivialize it.

00:53:54.300 --> 00:53:58.470
So in my own work, I'm always
seeking to find that balance.

