01:11:05.110 --> 01:11:06.220
So what did we do today?

01:11:08.870 --> 01:11:11.170
What did we do to citizenship?

01:11:11.170 --> 01:11:13.300
I'd like to think we kind
of unsettled it a bit.

01:11:13.300 --> 01:11:14.470
Right?

01:11:14.470 --> 01:11:16.090
Busted it apart.

01:11:16.090 --> 01:11:18.920
Is there anything
left to it anymore?

01:11:18.920 --> 01:11:22.330
We learned from Sabeel Rahman
that it's not one off, one on.

01:11:22.330 --> 01:11:23.360
It's not binary.

01:11:23.360 --> 01:11:25.280
It's not like a light switch.

01:11:25.280 --> 01:11:26.410
It's more smooth.

01:11:26.410 --> 01:11:30.410
It's functional,
continuous, convex.

01:11:30.410 --> 01:11:32.930
It gets undone by
economic power,

01:11:32.930 --> 01:11:35.900
to the extent that economic
relations can render

01:11:35.900 --> 01:11:40.860
it fictive, almost, as we
learned from Zephyr Teachout

01:11:40.860 --> 01:11:43.930
whose talk was really scary.

01:11:43.930 --> 01:11:46.920
But really persuasive.

01:11:46.920 --> 01:11:50.010
It has been used, as our
indigenous friends have

01:11:50.010 --> 01:11:54.750
reminded us, as a cudgel
to forcibly assimilate

01:11:54.750 --> 01:11:58.000
the indigenous peoples of
North America and elsewhere.

01:11:58.000 --> 01:11:59.640
We learned that
from Rosita Worl.

01:11:59.640 --> 01:12:02.520
We learned that
from Jill Doerfler.

01:12:02.520 --> 01:12:07.260
Citizenship has been
used to reassemble

01:12:07.260 --> 01:12:12.930
a fictional white majority,
a fictional white community

01:12:12.930 --> 01:12:16.430
as Professor Minna
Stern just noted.

01:12:16.430 --> 01:12:21.530
And as Lyndsey [INAUDIBLE]
just reminded us,

01:12:21.530 --> 01:12:25.900
citizenship's
residual categories

01:12:25.900 --> 01:12:29.300
define those outside
of them as people,

01:12:29.300 --> 01:12:31.790
as agents, of somehow
having less value,

01:12:31.790 --> 01:12:36.440
less permanence, less
belonging than those within.

01:12:36.440 --> 01:12:39.590
And finally, perhaps
more most poignantly,

01:12:39.590 --> 01:12:43.640
[INAUDIBLE] reminded us
that sometimes citizenship

01:12:43.640 --> 01:12:45.470
isn't enough.

01:12:45.470 --> 01:12:50.740
You can have all the
formal citizenship,

01:12:50.740 --> 01:12:54.230
but it doesn't deliver
the antibiotics, the food,

01:12:54.230 --> 01:12:55.990
the water that
needs to be there.

01:12:59.040 --> 01:13:01.620
I'm not ready to throw in
the towel on citizenship

01:13:01.620 --> 01:13:02.280
yet, though.

01:13:02.280 --> 01:13:03.930
And while I don't
have any answers,

01:13:03.930 --> 01:13:06.870
let me just point
a couple of paths

01:13:06.870 --> 01:13:11.160
forward, really not so much for
progress in the global sense,

01:13:11.160 --> 01:13:13.650
but in ways that we can think
about it that are really

01:13:13.650 --> 01:13:18.390
just inspired by if not just
pure repetitions of what

01:13:18.390 --> 01:13:20.760
you heard earlier today.

01:13:20.760 --> 01:13:25.510
We need more than
citizenship, obviously.

01:13:25.510 --> 01:13:28.210
But maybe we also need a
transformed citizenship.

01:13:28.210 --> 01:13:31.660
Maybe unsettling
citizenship, making

01:13:31.660 --> 01:13:35.260
it unruly, unruled
in that respect,

01:13:35.260 --> 01:13:38.080
is exactly what we
need to save it.

01:13:38.080 --> 01:13:41.410
And once saved or once
appropriately transformed,

01:13:41.410 --> 01:13:45.070
maybe we need what it provides,
namely rights and governments

01:13:45.070 --> 01:13:47.890
in the best sense.

01:13:47.890 --> 01:13:50.350
Maybe we need the
kind of citizenship

01:13:50.350 --> 01:13:52.510
that respects the
sovereignty and treaties

01:13:52.510 --> 01:13:55.570
of indigenous
communities and citizens.

01:13:55.570 --> 01:13:59.500
Maybe we need governmental
resources properly

01:13:59.500 --> 01:14:03.460
laid out to protect human rights
and those most vulnerable,

01:14:03.460 --> 01:14:06.190
whether they're the
poor, whether they're

01:14:06.190 --> 01:14:09.460
the refugee, whether they're
indigenous citizens, what

01:14:09.460 --> 01:14:11.110
have you.

01:14:11.110 --> 01:14:12.910
Maybe we need a more
encompassing vision

01:14:12.910 --> 01:14:16.510
of citizenship that
rejects racist thinking

01:14:16.510 --> 01:14:21.640
and imagined Edens or that
refashions the museum much

01:14:21.640 --> 01:14:26.290
as Pap Ndiaye is doing
right now in Paris.

01:14:26.290 --> 01:14:29.080
And maybe we need a form of
citizenship that calls us

01:14:29.080 --> 01:14:34.730
to the kind of commitment and
vitality that Mayor Carmen

01:14:34.730 --> 01:14:38.380
Yulín Cruz Soto
called us to today.

01:14:38.380 --> 01:14:42.970
And on that note, I really
can't do any better.

01:14:42.970 --> 01:14:45.910
And none of us could do
any better than the way

01:14:45.910 --> 01:14:49.990
that she marshaled
our aspirations

01:14:49.990 --> 01:14:52.090
at that wonderful
keynote address.

01:14:52.090 --> 01:14:54.040
I hope that and
all of this remain

01:14:54.040 --> 01:14:58.750
with you, the questions, the
aspirations, the inspiration.

01:14:58.750 --> 01:15:00.048
Go on and be good citizens.

